{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1781459245610,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"id":"prt_ec73eda29001hr2WucwQQfv7aG","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","snapshot":"3c8ebfafb1b58b9722f814b1b084b0a262b2c514","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459247451,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_0b177f5c5dcd4433a8e3fe18","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/tool_surface.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/tool_surface.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Figma CLI Tool Surface\"\n3: description: \"The figma-ds-cli command surface classified read-only / mutating / destructive / arbitrary, plus the surface / gate / omit policy, the explicit destructive set with per-command rollback, the eval/raw/run arbitrary-mutation rule, the local-export no-overwrite rule, and the live --help verification requirement.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"figma cli command gating\"\n6:   - \"figma-ds-cli tool surface\"\n7:   - \"figma destructive commands\"\n8:   - \"figma read-only vs mutating\"\n9:   - \"figma eval raw run rule\"\n10: importance_tier: \"normal\"\n11: contextType: \"implementation\"\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Figma CLI Tool Surface\n15: \n16: > **IMPORTANT:** This taxonomy was built from a read-only source scan of the silships `figma-cli` repo (`main`, package `figma-ds-cli@1.2.0`) plus its `REFERENCE.md` / `CLAUDE.md`. The command surface **drifts** between `REFERENCE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and the actual `src/commands/*.js` (documented commands such as `voice`, `chat`, `prop combine`, and the `create rect/circle/...` primitives were NOT found in the source scan). **Always verify a command with `<bin> <command> --help` before relying on it**, and gate every mutating or destructive verb. The CLI was not installed or executed during this analysis, so every example below is **illustrative; verify with `--help`**.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Core Principle\n23: \n24: Surface read-only commands freely, gate every mutating verb behind confirmation plus an explicit target plus a one-line rollback, treat the explicit destructive set as the strictest case (confirm + explicit target + rollback, prefer duplicate-first), and treat `eval` / `raw` / `run` as arbitrary mutation that must be reviewed before it runs. The canonical binary is **`figma-ds-cli`**; the source surface is the only source of truth and it drifts from the docs.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Decide whether a `figma-ds-cli` command is safe to call unprompted, must be gated, or is destructive and needs confirmation plus a rollback.\n29: - Confirm the gating class of any command before authoring, modifying, deleting, or exporting in a Figma document.\n30: - Reach for the destructive set and rollback table before any delete / clear / undo / unwrap / uninstall / unlink operation.\n31: \n32: ### Key Sources\n33: \n34: - [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, and command examples.\n35: - [mcp_wiring.md](mcp_wiring.md) - the optional Framelink Figma MCP via Code Mode (a separate, opt-in surface, not part of this CLI gating).\n36: \n37: Claims here are tagged **READ-ONLY**, **MUTATING**, **DESTRUCTIVE**, or **ARBITRARY** as defined in Section 2, and were read from the repo source scan recorded in the packet research digest (`151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research`). They are **source-verified for repo `main`**, not live-verified against an installed binary.\n38: \n39: ### The naming trap (read first)\n40: \n41: The canonical binary is **`figma-ds-cli`** (silships, npm `figma-ds-cli`, MIT). The npm package literally named **`figma-cli` is an UNRELATED tool** (unic/figma-cli, bin `figma`). **NEVER `npm i -g figma-cli`.** The `figma-cli` command only exists when installed from the silships repo (`main` exposes both `figma-ds-cli` and `figma-cli`); npm `latest` (`1.0.0`) exposes only `figma-ds-cli`. This document writes every command with `figma-ds-cli`.\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 2. THE FOUR CLASSES\n46: \n47: Every command falls into exactly one gating class. The class drives the exposure policy in Section 4.\n48: \n49: - **READ-ONLY** — reads Figma or local state, or writes an **export file**, without changing the Figma document or app/config state. Safe to surface. **Caveat:** any command that writes a local file (`extract`, `export*`, `verify --save`, `analyze-url --screenshot`, `api setup/index`) must use an **explicit output path and never silently overwrite** an existing file (see Section 5).\n50: - **MUTATING** — changes the Figma document, the current selection, or local tool / app / plugin / config state. Gate behind confirmation + an explicit target + a one-line rollback. Includes all authoring, layout, token, binding, variant, import, app-level connect/patch/daemon, and `init-agent` verbs.\n51: - **DESTRUCTIVE** — deletes Figma document content, variables, collections, annotations, grids, or removes an installed/local resource. The strictest case: confirm + **explicit target** + a stated rollback, and **prefer duplicating** the file/page/selection first. Never via an active-selection fallback. The explicit set + per-command rollback is Section 6.\n52: - **ARBITRARY** — `eval`, `run`, and `raw` execute arbitrary Figma Plugin API code or arbitrary `figma-use` commands. They can do **anything** (read, mutate, or delete). Treat as MUTATING-at-minimum, **review the code/command before running**, and never run them on an exploratory hunch (Section 7).\n53: \n54: > Tag meanings used in the table below: `READ-ONLY`, `MUTATING`, `DESTRUCTIVE`, `ARBITRARY`. Where a single command name has read-only and write sub-verbs (`component prop`, `dev`, `section`, `grid`, `annotate`), the per-sub-verb class is called out.\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## 3. THE COMMAND SURFACE (CLASSIFIED BY GROUP)\n59: \n60: Source-verified against repo `main` `src/commands/*.js`, `REFERENCE.md`, and `CLAUDE.md`. **Verify with `--help` before relying on any row** — the surface drifts (Section 8).\n61: \n62: | Group | Command | Class | Notes |\n63: | ----- | ------- | ----- | ----- |\n64: | Setup | `figma-ds-cli` (first run) | MUTATING | First-run wizard: checks Node, may patch Figma, starts Figma. App-level. |\n65: | Setup | `init` / `setup` | MUTATING | Interactive setup; `setup` aliases `init`. App-level. |\n66: | Setup | `connect [--safe]` | MUTATING | `--safe` = plugin bridge (no patch, DEFAULT). Bare `connect` = yolo `app.asar` patch (GATE: consent + rollback). App-level. |\n67: | Setup | `unpatch` | MUTATING | Restores the original `app.asar` string (the yolo rollback). App-level. |\n68: | Setup | `status` | READ-ONLY | Checks CDP + daemon status. |\n69: | Setup | `diagnose` | READ-ONLY | System compatibility + connection status. |\n70: | Daemon | `daemon status [--debug]` | READ-ONLY | Daemon health / token diagnostics. |\n71: | Daemon | `daemon diagnose` | READ-ONLY | Full daemon troubleshooting. |\n72: | Daemon | `daemon start [--force]` | MUTATING | Starts daemon, generates token. App-level. |\n73: | Daemon | `daemon stop` | MUTATING | Stops daemon. App-level. |\n74: | Daemon | `daemon restart` | MUTATING | Restarts daemon, regenerates token. App-level. |\n75: | Daemon | `daemon reconnect` | MUTATING | Reconnects daemon to Figma. App-level. |\n76: | Agent setup | `init-agent [--tool claude\\|cursor\\|both] [--force]` | MUTATING | Writes `AGENTS.md` and/or `.cursor/rules/figma-cli.mdc` into the **working repo**. Not default-run. |\n77: | Design I/O | `extract [output] [--pages] [--sections] [--selection] [--split\\|--no-split]` | READ-ONLY | Writes `DESIGN.md`; auto-splits large structure into `DESIGN-structure/`. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n78: | Design I/O | `spec <component> [-f file] [--check nodeId] [--tolerance px]` | READ-ONLY | Reads `DESIGN.md` spec; `--check` measures a built node, non-zero exit on mismatch. |\n79: | Design I/O | `import <source> [-c] [--save] [--type ...] [--print-context]` | MUTATING | Imports DESIGN.md / Tailwind / CSS / tokens.json / Storybook into variables. |\n80: | Variables | `var list` / `var find <pattern>` | READ-ONLY | Lists / finds variables. |\n81: | Variables | `var visualize [collection]` | MUTATING | Creates color swatches on canvas. |\n82: | Variables | `var create <name> ...` / `var create-batch <json> -c` | MUTATING | Creates one / many variables. |\n83: | Variables | `var bind-batch <json>` / `var set-batch <json>` / `var rename-batch <json>` | MUTATING | Batch bind / set / rename across nodes. |\n84: | Variables | `var delete-all [-c collection]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes all local variables/collections (or one collection's). |\n85: | Variables | `var delete-batch <nodeIds>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes multiple nodes by id. |\n86: | Collections | `collections list` / `col list` | READ-ONLY | Lists collections. |\n87: | Collections | `collections create <name>` / `col create <name>` | MUTATING | Creates a collection. |\n88: | Tokens | `tokens overlap <collections...> [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Compares token names across collections. |\n89: | Tokens | `tokens tailwind\\|preset\\|shadcn\\|spacing\\|radii\\|ds\\|components` | MUTATING | Creates token scales / presets / base design system. |\n90: | Tokens | `tokens import <file>` / `tokens import-design-md <file>` | MUTATING | Imports JSON / DESIGN.md tokens. |\n91: | Tokens | `tokens add <name> <value> [-c] [-t]` | MUTATING | Adds one token. |\n92: | Binding | `bind list [-t COLOR\\|FLOAT]` | READ-ONLY | Lists bindable variables. |\n93: | Binding | `bind fill\\|stroke\\|radius\\|gap\\|padding <varName> [-n] [-s]` | MUTATING | Binds a node property to a variable. |\n94: | Creation | `render <jsx> ...` / `render-batch <jsxArray> ...` | MUTATING | Renders JSX to Figma. Preferred over `eval` for visual nodes. |\n95: | Creation | `undo` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes the node(s) created by the latest render / render-batch. |\n96: | Creation | `create frame\\|icon\\|image ...` | MUTATING | Creates a frame / Iconify icon / image-from-URL node. |\n97: | Creation | `rect\\|ellipse\\|text\\|line\\|component\\|group\\|autolayout\\|al` | MUTATING | Top-level primitive aliases (source-proven; `REFERENCE.md` `create rect/...` form is drift — verify with `--help`). |\n98: | Layout | `sizing hug\\|fill\\|fixed ...` | MUTATING | Sets auto-layout sizing. |\n99: | Layout | `padding\\|pad` / `gap` / `align` | MUTATING | Sets padding / gap / alignment. |\n100: | Layout | `set autolayout\\|al ...` / `set pin <edge> ...` | MUTATING | Applies auto-layout / constraints. |\n101: | Layout | `arrange [-g] [-c]` | MUTATING | Rearranges all top-level frames (repositions; not a delete). |\n102: | Layout | `unstack [-g] [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Spreads overlapping nodes; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n103: | Modification | `set fill\\|stroke\\|radius\\|size\\|scale\\|pos\\|opacity\\|name\\|text ...` | MUTATING | Changes matched node properties. |\n104: | Modification | `use <collection>` / `theme <collection> [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Rebinds variable references; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n105: | Modification | `unwrap <nodeId> [--keep-wrapper]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Moves children out and **deletes the wrapper** unless `--keep-wrapper`. |\n106: | Query | `canvas info` / `canvas next` | READ-ONLY | Canvas bounds / next free position. |\n107: | Query | `find <name>` / `get [nodeId]` / `inspect <nodeId>` | READ-ONLY | Finds / reads node properties / spec. |\n108: | Query | `select <nodeId>` | MUTATING | Changes current selection only. |\n109: | Duplicate/delete | `duplicate\\|dup [nodeId] [--offset]` | MUTATING | Duplicates a node/selection (this is the preferred pre-delete rollback). |\n110: | Duplicate/delete | `delete\\|remove [nodeId]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a node/selection. |\n111: | Node | `node tree [nodeId]` / `node bindings [nodeId]` | READ-ONLY | Shows node tree / variable bindings. |\n112: | Node | `node to-component <nodeIds...>` | MUTATING | Converts frames to components. |\n113: | Node | `node delete <nodeIds...>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes nodes by id. |\n114: | Slots | `slot list [nodeId]` | READ-ONLY | Lists slots. |\n115: | Slots | `slot create\\|preferred\\|reset\\|convert\\|add ...` | MUTATING | Creates / configures slots. |\n116: | Variants | `sizes [nodeId]` / `variants from <ids> ...` | MUTATING | Generates size variants / a variant set. |\n117: | Variants | `combos [nodeId] [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Generates variant combinations; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n118: | shadcn | `shadcn list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available components. |\n119: | shadcn | `shadcn add [names...] [--all]` | MUTATING | Adds shadcn/ui components to canvas. |\n120: | Blocks | `blocks list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available blocks. |\n121: | Blocks | `blocks create <id>` | MUTATING | Creates a prebuilt UI block. |\n122: | Component props | `component prop list` | READ-ONLY | Lists component properties. |\n123: | Component props | `component prop add\\|combine` | MUTATING | Adds / combines component properties. |\n124: | Component props | `component prop delete` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a component property. |\n125: | Dev resources | `dev list` | READ-ONLY | Lists dev resource links. |\n126: | Dev resources | `dev link\\|edit` | MUTATING | Adds / edits dev resource links. |\n127: | Dev resources | `dev unlink` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes a dev resource link. |\n128: | Sections | `section list` | READ-ONLY | Lists sections. |\n129: | Sections | `section create\\|add` | MUTATING | Creates / assigns sections. |\n130: | Grids | `grid list` | READ-ONLY | Lists layout grids. |\n131: | Grids | `grid set` | MUTATING | Sets a layout grid. |\n132: | Grids | `grid clear` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Clears grid metadata. |\n133: | Annotations | `annotate list` | READ-ONLY | Lists annotations. |\n134: | Annotations | `annotate add` | MUTATING | Adds an annotation. |\n135: | Annotations | `annotate clear` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Clears annotations. |\n136: | Export | `export screenshot\\|node\\|css\\|tailwind ...` | READ-ONLY | Writes export files. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n137: | Export | `export-jsx [nodeId] [-o] [--pretty]` / `export-storybook [nodeId] [-o]` | READ-ONLY | Writes JSX / Storybook files. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n138: | Verify | `verify [nodeId] [--save path] [--measure]` | READ-ONLY | Returns / saves a screenshot + optional measurement JSON. No overwrite on `--save`. |\n139: | Analysis | `analyze colors\\|typography\\|spacing\\|clusters [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Reports usage / patterns. |\n140: | Analysis | `lint [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Lints the design. |\n141: | Analysis | `lint --fix` | MUTATING | `--fix` mutates the document. |\n142: | A11y | `a11y contrast\\|vision\\|touch\\|text\\|focus\\|audit ...` | READ-ONLY | Accessibility checks. |\n143: | URL/image | `analyze-url <url> [--screenshot]` | READ-ONLY | Extracts webpage CSS; `--screenshot` writes a local file (no overwrite). |\n144: | URL/image | `screenshot-url <url> ...` / `recreate-url <url> ...` | MUTATING | Imports a website screenshot / recreates a webpage **into Figma**. |\n145: | URL/image | `remove-bg [nodeId] [--api-key]` | MUTATING | Removes an image background; needs a remove.bg key (network). |\n146: | Gradient | `gradient extract <image> [--json]` (no `--apply-to`) | READ-ONLY | Extracts a gradient without applying. |\n147: | Gradient | `gradient extract ... --apply-to <nodeId>` / `gradient mesh <colors> ...` | MUTATING | Applies / creates a gradient on a node. |\n148: | FigJam | `fj list\\|info\\|nodes` | READ-ONLY | Lists FigJam pages / nodes. |\n149: | FigJam | `fj sticky\\|shape\\|text\\|connect\\|move\\|update ...` | MUTATING | Creates / edits FigJam content. |\n150: | FigJam | `fj delete <nodeId> [-p]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a FigJam node. |\n151: | FigJam | `fj eval <code> [-p]` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary FigJam eval — review before running (Section 7). |\n152: | Files | `files` | READ-ONLY | Lists open design files as JSON. |\n153: | Plugins | `plugins list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available plugins. |\n154: | Plugins | `plugins install\\|setup <name>` | MUTATING | Installs / sets up a plugin. |\n155: | Plugins | `plugins uninstall <name>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes an installed plugin resource. |\n156: | Plugin API docs | `api index\\|context\\|list\\|search\\|gap\\|age` | READ-ONLY | Reads the offline Plugin API docs. |\n157: | Plugin API docs | `api setup [--update]` | MUTATING | Writes local docs/index files (no overwrite). |\n158: | Config | `config get <key>` | READ-ONLY | Reads config. |\n159: | Config | `config set <key> <value>` | MUTATING | Writes local config (e.g. a removebg key). |\n160: | Raw/eval | `eval [code] [-f file]` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary Figma Plugin API code — review before running (Section 7). |\n161: | Raw/eval | `run <file>` | ARBITRARY | Alias for executing an eval file — review before running. |\n162: | Raw/eval | `raw <command...>` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary `figma-use` command — review before running. |\n163: \n164: > The full per-flag table (~130 rows) lives in the packet research raw output: `151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research/research/raw/iter-001.out`.\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ## 4. THE SURFACE / GATE / OMIT POLICY\n169: \n170: This policy is the spine of how the skill exposes the surface.\n171: \n172: ### Surface freely (READ-ONLY)\n173: \n174: Call these without ceremony, with one constraint — any read that **writes a local file** must use an explicit output path and must not overwrite (Section 5):\n175: \n176: `status`, `diagnose`, `daemon status`, `daemon diagnose`, `var list`, `var find`, `collections list`, `bind list`, `tokens overlap`, `extract`, `spec`, `canvas info`, `canvas next`, `find`, `get`, `inspect`, `node tree`, `node bindings`, `slot list`, `shadcn list`, `blocks list`, `component prop list`, `dev list`, `section list`, `grid list`, `annotate list`, `files`, `plugins list`, `config get`, `export *`, `export-jsx`, `export-storybook`, `verify`, `analyze *`, `lint` (no `--fix`), `a11y *`, `analyze-url`, `gradient extract` (no `--apply-to`), `fj list\\|info\\|nodes`, `api index\\|context\\|list\\|search\\|gap\\|age`, and the `--dry-run` forms of `unstack` / `use` / `theme` / `combos`.\n177: \n178: ### Surface but GATE (confirmation + explicit target + rollback note)\n179: \n180: Before any of these, state the effect and a one-line rollback, name the explicit target node/file/collection, and stop for confirmation:\n181: \n182: - **App-level:** `connect` (yolo patch — rollback `figma-ds-cli unpatch`), `unpatch`, `daemon start\\|stop\\|restart\\|reconnect`, `config set`, `plugins install\\|setup`, `api setup`, and **`init-agent`** (writes `AGENTS.md` / `.cursor/rules` into the working repo — never default-run).\n183: - **Doc-level authoring:** all `create*` / `render*` / primitive aliases, `tokens *` writes, `var create\\|create-batch\\|bind-batch\\|set-batch\\|rename-batch\\|visualize`, `bind *`, `set *`, layout verbs (`sizing\\|padding\\|gap\\|align\\|set autolayout\\|set pin\\|arrange\\|unstack`), `duplicate`, `use\\|theme`, `node to-component`, `slot` writes, `sizes\\|variants\\|combos`, `shadcn add`, `blocks create`, `component prop add\\|combine`, `dev link\\|edit`, `section create\\|add`, `grid set`, `annotate add`, `import`, `lint --fix`, `screenshot-url`, `recreate-url`, `remove-bg`, `gradient extract --apply-to`, `gradient mesh`, and `fj` write verbs.\n184: \n185: ### OMIT from the default path (destructive + arbitrary — explicit request only)\n186: \n187: Keep these out of the normal flow. Reach for them only on an explicit, specific user request, with the Section 6 / Section 7 ceremony:\n188: \n189: - **Destructive:** `var delete-all`, `var delete-batch`, `delete\\|remove`, `node delete`, `undo`, `unwrap`, `fj delete`, `plugins uninstall`, `dev unlink`, `component prop delete`, `grid clear`, `annotate clear`.\n190: - **Arbitrary mutation:** `eval`, `run`, `raw`, `fj eval`.\n191: \n192: Where two readings of a command disagreed (e.g. `arrange` reads as \"destructive\" in one source comment but only repositions), the **stricter gating wins** in the SURFACE/GATE choice and the **accurate class wins** in the table — `arrange` is MUTATING (repositions), not DESTRUCTIVE (no delete).\n193: \n194: ---\n195: \n196: ## 5. THE LOCAL-EXPORT NO-OVERWRITE RULE\n197: \n198: Read-only does not mean side-effect-free on the local filesystem. `extract`, `export *`, `export-jsx`, `export-storybook`, `verify --save`, `analyze-url --screenshot`, and `api setup\\|index` all **write files locally**.\n199: \n200: 1. **Always pass an explicit output path** (`-o file` / `[output]` / `--save path`). Do not rely on a default filename.\n201: 2. **Never silently overwrite.** Check for an existing file first; if the target exists, choose a new path or ask before clobbering it.\n202: 3. **Handle multi-file output.** `extract` auto-splits a large structure into a `DESIGN-structure/` directory above ~50k tokens — treat the export as a possible directory, not a single file.\n203: \n204: These are local-filesystem mutations even though the Figma document is untouched. They never need Figma-side rollback, but they must not destroy prior local work.\n205: \n206: ---\n207: \n208: ## 6. THE DESTRUCTIVE SET (CONFIRM + EXPLICIT TARGET + ROLLBACK)\n209: \n210: Never run any of these without an explicit target (id / name / collection) and a stated rollback. **Never via an active-selection fallback.** The strongest rollback is to **duplicate the file / page / selection first** (`figma-ds-cli duplicate`, or a Figma page/file duplicate) — Figma's own **Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z)** and **version history** are the primary safety nets; the per-command notes below name the most direct recovery.\n211: \n212: | Destructive command | What it deletes | One-line rollback |\n213: | ------------------- | --------------- | ----------------- |\n214: | `var delete-all [-c collection]` | All local variables/collections (or one collection's) | Figma Undo immediately; otherwise restore from version history — irreversible once the session closes, so **duplicate the file first**. |\n215: | `var delete-batch <nodeIds>` | The listed nodes | Figma Undo; else version history. Confirm the exact id list before running. |\n216: | `delete\\|remove [nodeId]` | A node / current selection | Figma Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z); duplicate the node first for a safe copy. |\n217: | `node delete <nodeIds...>` | Nodes by id | Figma Undo; duplicate the nodes first. Require the explicit id list, not the selection. |\n218: | `undo` | The node(s) from the latest render / render-batch | Re-run the original `render` / `render-batch` to recreate; there is no \"redo\" for this CLI verb. |\n219: | `unwrap <nodeId> [--keep-wrapper]` | The wrapper frame (children survive) | Pass `--keep-wrapper` to avoid the delete; else Figma Undo restores the wrapper. |\n220: | `fj delete <nodeId> [-p]` | A FigJam node | Figma Undo on the FigJam page; duplicate the page first for large clears. |\n221: | `plugins uninstall <name>` | An installed plugin resource | Re-install with `plugins install <name>` (re-runs setup; any local plugin config is lost). |\n222: | `dev unlink` | A dev resource link | Re-create with `dev link` using the original URL — record the URL before unlinking. |\n223: | `component prop delete` | A component property | Re-create with `component prop add`; Figma Undo if still in-session. Note the prop name/type first. |\n224: | `grid clear` | Layout grid metadata on a node | Figma Undo; else re-apply with `grid set` from the recorded grid spec. |\n225: | `annotate clear` | Annotations | Figma Undo; else re-add with `annotate add` — copy the annotation text first. |\n226: \n227: Rollback preference order, always: **(1) duplicate-first**, then **(2) Figma Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z) while still in-session**, then **(3) Figma version history**. State which one applies before you run the command.\n228: \n229: ---\n230: \n231: ## 7. THE ARBITRARY-MUTATION RULE (eval / raw / run / fj eval)\n232: \n233: `eval`, `run`, `raw`, and `fj eval` execute arbitrary Figma Plugin API code or arbitrary `figma-use` commands. They are not classified by name because the **payload** decides what they do — read, mutate, or delete.\n234: \n235: 1. **Treat them as MUTATING at minimum, and as potentially DESTRUCTIVE.** Apply the GATE ceremony (confirm + target + rollback) by default, and the DESTRUCTIVE ceremony if the payload can delete.\n236: 2. **Review the exact code / command before running it.** Never run `eval`/`run`/`raw` on an exploratory hunch or because the prompt \"sounds read-only.\"\n237: 3. **Prefer the purpose-built verb.** The upstream agent rules state: never use `eval` to create visual nodes (it bypasses positioning and guards) — use `render` / `render-batch`. Reach for arbitrary execution only when no dedicated command exists.\n238: 4. **Never delete existing user nodes** through arbitrary execution; the upstream generated rules prohibit it.\n239: \n240: ---\n241: \n242: ## 8. THE HARD RULE: VERIFY LIVE, GATE MUTATIONS\n243: \n244: The command surface drifts between `REFERENCE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and the actual `src/commands/*.js`. The investigation found documented-but-unregistered commands (`voice`, `chat`, `prop combine`) and primitive-name drift (`REFERENCE.md` shows `create rect/circle/...`; source proves `create frame/icon/image` plus top-level `rect|ellipse|text|line|component|group|autolayout`). All of it must be hedged.\n245: \n246: 1. **Verify with `<bin> <command> --help` before relying on a command.** A command in `REFERENCE.md`/`CLAUDE.md` may not exist in the installed binary, and flags differ between the npm `latest` (`1.0.0`) and repo `main` (`1.2.0`) builds. Examples in this skill are **illustrative; verify with `--help`.**\n247: 2. **Verify the binary identity first.** Prefer `figma-ds-cli`; only trust `figma-cli` after `--version`/`--help` confirms it is the silships tool (the npm `figma-cli` package is unrelated). **Never `npm i -g figma-cli`.**\n248: 3. **Gate every MUTATING verb** behind confirmation, an explicit target, and a one-line rollback.\n249: 4. **Apply the DESTRUCTIVE ceremony** (Section 6) to every command in the destructive set: confirm + explicit target + rollback, prefer duplicate-first, never via the active-selection fallback.\n250: 5. **Review every ARBITRARY payload** (Section 7) before it runs.\n251: 6. **Enforce the export no-overwrite rule** (Section 5) on every local-file write, including \"read-only\" exports.\n252: 7. **Never auto-apply the yolo `app.asar` patch** (`connect` without `--safe`) without explicit consent and a stated `figma-ds-cli unpatch` rollback. Prefer `connect --safe`.\n253: 8. **Never expose the daemon token** (`~/.figma-ds-cli/.daemon-token`) in user-facing output; keep the daemon bound to `127.0.0.1`.\n254: \n255: ---\n256: \n257: ## 9. ESCALATION\n258: \n259: - **A command is not in this table, or `--help` disagrees with it.** Stop and verify with `<bin> <command> --help`; do not guess a class. The source drifts (Section 8).\n260: - **A destructive verb, a broad delete/undo/unwrap, or an arbitrary `eval`/`raw`/`run` is requested.** Describe the effect and the rollback, name the explicit target, then stop and wait for confirmation.\n261: - **The yolo patch is requested.** Surface the `app.asar` modification, the Figma-update fragility, and the `figma-ds-cli unpatch` rollback; prefer `connect --safe`; wait for consent.\n262: - **An export would overwrite an existing file.** Stop, name the conflicting path, and ask for a new path or explicit overwrite approval.\n263: - **Figma Desktop is not open or the daemon is unhealthy.** None of these commands work without the live Desktop session and a healthy daemon — escalate to setup before mutating.\n264: \n265: ---\n266: \n267: ## 10. REFERENCES\n268: \n269: - [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, command examples.\n270: - [mcp_wiring.md](mcp_wiring.md) - the optional Framelink Figma MCP via Code Mode (separate, opt-in surface).\n271: - [troubleshooting.md](troubleshooting.md) - failure modes and fixes.\n272: - [SKILL.md](../SKILL.md) - the skill contract this reference supports.\n273: - Packet research digest: `151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research/research/iterations/iteration-001.md` (and `research/raw/iter-001.out` for the full per-flag table).\n\n(End of file - total 273 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Figma CLI Tool Surface\"\ndescription: \"The figma-ds-cli command surface classified read-only / mutating / destructive / arbitrary, plus the surface / gate / omit policy, the explicit destructive set with per-command rollback, the eval/raw/run arbitrary-mutation rule, the local-export no-overwrite rule, and the live --help verification requirement.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"figma cli command gating\"\n  - \"figma-ds-cli tool surface\"\n  - \"figma destructive commands\"\n  - \"figma read-only vs mutating\"\n  - \"figma eval raw run rule\"\nimportance_tier: \"normal\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n---\n\n# Figma CLI Tool Surface\n\n> **IMPORTANT:** This taxonomy was built from a read-only source scan of the silships `figma-cli` repo (`main`, package `figma-ds-cli@1.2.0`) plus its `REFERENCE.md` / `CLAUDE.md`. The command surface **drifts** between `REFERENCE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and the actual `src/commands/*.js` (documented commands such as `voice`, `chat`, `prop combine`, and the `create rect/circle/...` primitives were NOT found in the source scan). **Always verify a command with `<bin> <command> --help` before relying on it**, and gate every mutating or destructive verb. The CLI was not installed or executed during this analysis, so every example below is **illustrative; verify with `--help`**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/tool_surface.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Figma CLI Tool Surface\"\ndescription: \"The figma-ds-cli command surface classified read-only / mutating / destructive / arbitrary, plus the surface / gate / omit policy, the explicit destructive set with per-command rollback, the eval/raw/run arbitrary-mutation rule, the local-export no-overwrite rule, and the live --help verification requirement.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"figma cli command gating\"\n  - \"figma-ds-cli tool surface\"\n  - \"figma destructive commands\"\n  - \"figma read-only vs mutating\"\n  - \"figma eval raw run rule\"\nimportance_tier: \"normal\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n---\n\n# Figma CLI Tool Surface\n\n> **IMPORTANT:** This taxonomy was built from a read-only source scan of the silships `figma-cli` repo (`main`, package `figma-ds-cli@1.2.0`) plus its `REFERENCE.md` / `CLAUDE.md`. The command surface **drifts** between `REFERENCE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and the actual `src/commands/*.js` (documented commands such as `voice`, `chat`, `prop combine`, and the `create rect/circle/...` primitives were NOT found in the source scan). **Always verify a command with `<bin> <command> --help` before relying on it**, and gate every mutating or destructive verb. The CLI was not installed or executed during this analysis, so every example below is **illustrative; verify with `--help`**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\nSurface read-only commands freely, gate every mutating verb behind confirmation plus an explicit target plus a one-line rollback, treat the explicit destructive set as the strictest case (confirm + explicit target + rollback, prefer duplicate-first), and treat `eval` / `raw` / `run` as arbitrary mutation that must be reviewed before it runs. The canonical binary is **`figma-ds-cli`**; the source surface is the only source of truth and it drifts from the docs.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Decide whether a `figma-ds-cli` command is safe to call unprompted, must be gated, or is destructive and needs confirmation plus a rollback.\n- Confirm the gating class of any command before authoring, modifying, deleting, or exporting in a Figma document.\n- Reach for the destructive set and rollback table before any delete / clear / undo / unwrap / uninstall / unlink operation.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n- [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, and command examples.\n- [mcp_wiring.md](mcp_wiring.md) - the optional Framelink Figma MCP via Code Mode (a separate, opt-in surface, not part of this CLI gating).\n\nClaims here are tagged **READ-ONLY**, **MUTATING**, **DESTRUCTIVE**, or **ARBITRARY** as defined in Section 2, and were read from the repo source scan recorded in the packet research digest (`151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research`). They are **source-verified for repo `main`**, not live-verified against an installed binary.\n\n### The naming trap (read first)\n\nThe canonical binary is **`figma-ds-cli`** (silships, npm `figma-ds-cli`, MIT). The npm package literally named **`figma-cli` is an UNRELATED tool** (unic/figma-cli, bin `figma`). **NEVER `npm i -g figma-cli`.** The `figma-cli` command only exists when installed from the silships repo (`main` exposes both `figma-ds-cli` and `figma-cli`); npm `latest` (`1.0.0`) exposes only `figma-ds-cli`. This document writes every command with `figma-ds-cli`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE FOUR CLASSES\n\nEvery command falls into exactly one gating class. The class drives the exposure policy in Section 4.\n\n- **READ-ONLY** — reads Figma or local state, or writes an **export file**, without changing the Figma document or app/config state. Safe to surface. **Caveat:** any command that writes a local file (`extract`, `export*`, `verify --save`, `analyze-url --screenshot`, `api setup/index`) must use an **explicit output path and never silently overwrite** an existing file (see Section 5).\n- **MUTATING** — changes the Figma document, the current selection, or local tool / app / plugin / config state. Gate behind confirmation + an explicit target + a one-line rollback. Includes all authoring, layout, token, binding, variant, import, app-level connect/patch/daemon, and `init-agent` verbs.\n- **DESTRUCTIVE** — deletes Figma document content, variables, collections, annotations, grids, or removes an installed/local resource. The strictest case: confirm + **explicit target** + a stated rollback, and **prefer duplicating** the file/page/selection first. Never via an active-selection fallback. The explicit set + per-command rollback is Section 6.\n- **ARBITRARY** — `eval`, `run`, and `raw` execute arbitrary Figma Plugin API code or arbitrary `figma-use` commands. They can do **anything** (read, mutate, or delete). Treat as MUTATING-at-minimum, **review the code/command before running**, and never run them on an exploratory hunch (Section 7).\n\n> Tag meanings used in the table below: `READ-ONLY`, `MUTATING`, `DESTRUCTIVE`, `ARBITRARY`. Where a single command name has read-only and write sub-verbs (`component prop`, `dev`, `section`, `grid`, `annotate`), the per-sub-verb class is called out.\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE COMMAND SURFACE (CLASSIFIED BY GROUP)\n\nSource-verified against repo `main` `src/commands/*.js`, `REFERENCE.md`, and `CLAUDE.md`. **Verify with `--help` before relying on any row** — the surface drifts (Section 8).\n\n| Group | Command | Class | Notes |\n| ----- | ------- | ----- | ----- |\n| Setup | `figma-ds-cli` (first run) | MUTATING | First-run wizard: checks Node, may patch Figma, starts Figma. App-level. |\n| Setup | `init` / `setup` | MUTATING | Interactive setup; `setup` aliases `init`. App-level. |\n| Setup | `connect [--safe]` | MUTATING | `--safe` = plugin bridge (no patch, DEFAULT). Bare `connect` = yolo `app.asar` patch (GATE: consent + rollback). App-level. |\n| Setup | `unpatch` | MUTATING | Restores the original `app.asar` string (the yolo rollback). App-level. |\n| Setup | `status` | READ-ONLY | Checks CDP + daemon status. |\n| Setup | `diagnose` | READ-ONLY | System compatibility + connection status. |\n| Daemon | `daemon status [--debug]` | READ-ONLY | Daemon health / token diagnostics. |\n| Daemon | `daemon diagnose` | READ-ONLY | Full daemon troubleshooting. |\n| Daemon | `daemon start [--force]` | MUTATING | Starts daemon, generates token. App-level. |\n| Daemon | `daemon stop` | MUTATING | Stops daemon. App-level. |\n| Daemon | `daemon restart` | MUTATING | Restarts daemon, regenerates token. App-level. |\n| Daemon | `daemon reconnect` | MUTATING | Reconnects daemon to Figma. App-level. |\n| Agent setup | `init-agent [--tool claude\\|cursor\\|both] [--force]` | MUTATING | Writes `AGENTS.md` and/or `.cursor/rules/figma-cli.mdc` into the **working repo**. Not default-run. |\n| Design I/O | `extract [output] [--pages] [--sections] [--selection] [--split\\|--no-split]` | READ-ONLY | Writes `DESIGN.md`; auto-splits large structure into `DESIGN-structure/`. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n| Design I/O | `spec <component> [-f file] [--check nodeId] [--tolerance px]` | READ-ONLY | Reads `DESIGN.md` spec; `--check` measures a built node, non-zero exit on mismatch. |\n| Design I/O | `import <source> [-c] [--save] [--type ...] [--print-context]` | MUTATING | Imports DESIGN.md / Tailwind / CSS / tokens.json / Storybook into variables. |\n| Variables | `var list` / `var find <pattern>` | READ-ONLY | Lists / finds variables. |\n| Variables | `var visualize [collection]` | MUTATING | Creates color swatches on canvas. |\n| Variables | `var create <name> ...` / `var create-batch <json> -c` | MUTATING | Creates one / many variables. |\n| Variables | `var bind-batch <json>` / `var set-batch <json>` / `var rename-batch <json>` | MUTATING | Batch bind / set / rename across nodes. |\n| Variables | `var delete-all [-c collection]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes all local variables/collections (or one collection's). |\n| Variables | `var delete-batch <nodeIds>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes multiple nodes by id. |\n| Collections | `collections list` / `col list` | READ-ONLY | Lists collections. |\n| Collections | `collections create <name>` / `col create <name>` | MUTATING | Creates a collection. |\n| Tokens | `tokens overlap <collections...> [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Compares token names across collections. |\n| Tokens | `tokens tailwind\\|preset\\|shadcn\\|spacing\\|radii\\|ds\\|components` | MUTATING | Creates token scales / presets / base design system. |\n| Tokens | `tokens import <file>` / `tokens import-design-md <file>` | MUTATING | Imports JSON / DESIGN.md tokens. |\n| Tokens | `tokens add <name> <value> [-c] [-t]` | MUTATING | Adds one token. |\n| Binding | `bind list [-t COLOR\\|FLOAT]` | READ-ONLY | Lists bindable variables. |\n| Binding | `bind fill\\|stroke\\|radius\\|gap\\|padding <varName> [-n] [-s]` | MUTATING | Binds a node property to a variable. |\n| Creation | `render <jsx> ...` / `render-batch <jsxArray> ...` | MUTATING | Renders JSX to Figma. Preferred over `eval` for visual nodes. |\n| Creation | `undo` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes the node(s) created by the latest render / render-batch. |\n| Creation | `create frame\\|icon\\|image ...` | MUTATING | Creates a frame / Iconify icon / image-from-URL node. |\n| Creation | `rect\\|ellipse\\|text\\|line\\|component\\|group\\|autolayout\\|al` | MUTATING | Top-level primitive aliases (source-proven; `REFERENCE.md` `create rect/...` form is drift — verify with `--help`). |\n| Layout | `sizing hug\\|fill\\|fixed ...` | MUTATING | Sets auto-layout sizing. |\n| Layout | `padding\\|pad` / `gap` / `align` | MUTATING | Sets padding / gap / alignment. |\n| Layout | `set autolayout\\|al ...` / `set pin <edge> ...` | MUTATING | Applies auto-layout / constraints. |\n| Layout | `arrange [-g] [-c]` | MUTATING | Rearranges all top-level frames (repositions; not a delete). |\n| Layout | `unstack [-g] [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Spreads overlapping nodes; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n| Modification | `set fill\\|stroke\\|radius\\|size\\|scale\\|pos\\|opacity\\|name\\|text ...` | MUTATING | Changes matched node properties. |\n| Modification | `use <collection>` / `theme <collection> [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Rebinds variable references; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n| Modification | `unwrap <nodeId> [--keep-wrapper]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Moves children out and **deletes the wrapper** unless `--keep-wrapper`. |\n| Query | `canvas info` / `canvas next` | READ-ONLY | Canvas bounds / next free position. |\n| Query | `find <name>` / `get [nodeId]` / `inspect <nodeId>` | READ-ONLY | Finds / reads node properties / spec. |\n| Query | `select <nodeId>` | MUTATING | Changes current selection only. |\n| Duplicate/delete | `duplicate\\|dup [nodeId] [--offset]` | MUTATING | Duplicates a node/selection (this is the preferred pre-delete rollback). |\n| Duplicate/delete | `delete\\|remove [nodeId]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a node/selection. |\n| Node | `node tree [nodeId]` / `node bindings [nodeId]` | READ-ONLY | Shows node tree / variable bindings. |\n| Node | `node to-component <nodeIds...>` | MUTATING | Converts frames to components. |\n| Node | `node delete <nodeIds...>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes nodes by id. |\n| Slots | `slot list [nodeId]` | READ-ONLY | Lists slots. |\n| Slots | `slot create\\|preferred\\|reset\\|convert\\|add ...` | MUTATING | Creates / configures slots. |\n| Variants | `sizes [nodeId]` / `variants from <ids> ...` | MUTATING | Generates size variants / a variant set. |\n| Variants | `combos [nodeId] [--dry-run]` | MUTATING | Generates variant combinations; `--dry-run` is READ-ONLY. |\n| shadcn | `shadcn list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available components. |\n| shadcn | `shadcn add [names...] [--all]` | MUTATING | Adds shadcn/ui components to canvas. |\n| Blocks | `blocks list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available blocks. |\n| Blocks | `blocks create <id>` | MUTATING | Creates a prebuilt UI block. |\n| Component props | `component prop list` | READ-ONLY | Lists component properties. |\n| Component props | `component prop add\\|combine` | MUTATING | Adds / combines component properties. |\n| Component props | `component prop delete` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a component property. |\n| Dev resources | `dev list` | READ-ONLY | Lists dev resource links. |\n| Dev resources | `dev link\\|edit` | MUTATING | Adds / edits dev resource links. |\n| Dev resources | `dev unlink` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes a dev resource link. |\n| Sections | `section list` | READ-ONLY | Lists sections. |\n| Sections | `section create\\|add` | MUTATING | Creates / assigns sections. |\n| Grids | `grid list` | READ-ONLY | Lists layout grids. |\n| Grids | `grid set` | MUTATING | Sets a layout grid. |\n| Grids | `grid clear` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Clears grid metadata. |\n| Annotations | `annotate list` | READ-ONLY | Lists annotations. |\n| Annotations | `annotate add` | MUTATING | Adds an annotation. |\n| Annotations | `annotate clear` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Clears annotations. |\n| Export | `export screenshot\\|node\\|css\\|tailwind ...` | READ-ONLY | Writes export files. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n| Export | `export-jsx [nodeId] [-o] [--pretty]` / `export-storybook [nodeId] [-o]` | READ-ONLY | Writes JSX / Storybook files. Explicit output path; no overwrite. |\n| Verify | `verify [nodeId] [--save path] [--measure]` | READ-ONLY | Returns / saves a screenshot + optional measurement JSON. No overwrite on `--save`. |\n| Analysis | `analyze colors\\|typography\\|spacing\\|clusters [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Reports usage / patterns. |\n| Analysis | `lint [--json]` | READ-ONLY | Lints the design. |\n| Analysis | `lint --fix` | MUTATING | `--fix` mutates the document. |\n| A11y | `a11y contrast\\|vision\\|touch\\|text\\|focus\\|audit ...` | READ-ONLY | Accessibility checks. |\n| URL/image | `analyze-url <url> [--screenshot]` | READ-ONLY | Extracts webpage CSS; `--screenshot` writes a local file (no overwrite). |\n| URL/image | `screenshot-url <url> ...` / `recreate-url <url> ...` | MUTATING | Imports a website screenshot / recreates a webpage **into Figma**. |\n| URL/image | `remove-bg [nodeId] [--api-key]` | MUTATING | Removes an image background; needs a remove.bg key (network). |\n| Gradient | `gradient extract <image> [--json]` (no `--apply-to`) | READ-ONLY | Extracts a gradient without applying. |\n| Gradient | `gradient extract ... --apply-to <nodeId>` / `gradient mesh <colors> ...` | MUTATING | Applies / creates a gradient on a node. |\n| FigJam | `fj list\\|info\\|nodes` | READ-ONLY | Lists FigJam pages / nodes. |\n| FigJam | `fj sticky\\|shape\\|text\\|connect\\|move\\|update ...` | MUTATING | Creates / edits FigJam content. |\n| FigJam | `fj delete <nodeId> [-p]` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Deletes a FigJam node. |\n| FigJam | `fj eval <code> [-p]` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary FigJam eval — review before running (Section 7). |\n| Files | `files` | READ-ONLY | Lists open design files as JSON. |\n| Plugins | `plugins list` | READ-ONLY | Lists available plugins. |\n| Plugins | `plugins install\\|setup <name>` | MUTATING | Installs / sets up a plugin. |\n| Plugins | `plugins uninstall <name>` | **DESTRUCTIVE** | Removes an installed plugin resource. |\n| Plugin API docs | `api index\\|context\\|list\\|search\\|gap\\|age` | READ-ONLY | Reads the offline Plugin API docs. |\n| Plugin API docs | `api setup [--update]` | MUTATING | Writes local docs/index files (no overwrite). |\n| Config | `config get <key>` | READ-ONLY | Reads config. |\n| Config | `config set <key> <value>` | MUTATING | Writes local config (e.g. a removebg key). |\n| Raw/eval | `eval [code] [-f file]` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary Figma Plugin API code — review before running (Section 7). |\n| Raw/eval | `run <file>` | ARBITRARY | Alias for executing an eval file — review before running. |\n| Raw/eval | `raw <command...>` | ARBITRARY | Arbitrary `figma-use` command — review before running. |\n\n> The full per-flag table (~130 rows) lives in the packet research raw output: `151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research/research/raw/iter-001.out`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. THE SURFACE / GATE / OMIT POLICY\n\nThis policy is the spine of how the skill exposes the surface.\n\n### Surface freely (READ-ONLY)\n\nCall these without ceremony, with one constraint — any read that **writes a local file** must use an explicit output path and must not overwrite (Section 5):\n\n`status`, `diagnose`, `daemon status`, `daemon diagnose`, `var list`, `var find`, `collections list`, `bind list`, `tokens overlap`, `extract`, `spec`, `canvas info`, `canvas next`, `find`, `get`, `inspect`, `node tree`, `node bindings`, `slot list`, `shadcn list`, `blocks list`, `component prop list`, `dev list`, `section list`, `grid list`, `annotate list`, `files`, `plugins list`, `config get`, `export *`, `export-jsx`, `export-storybook`, `verify`, `analyze *`, `lint` (no `--fix`), `a11y *`, `analyze-url`, `gradient extract` (no `--apply-to`), `fj list\\|info\\|nodes`, `api index\\|context\\|list\\|search\\|gap\\|age`, and the `--dry-run` forms of `unstack` / `use` / `theme` / `combos`.\n\n### Surface but GATE (confirmation + explicit target + rollback note)\n\nBefore any of these, state the effect and a one-line rollback, name the explicit target node/file/collection, and stop for confirmation:\n\n- **App-level:** `connect` (yolo patch — rollback `figma-ds-cli unpatch`), `unpatch`, `daemon start\\|stop\\|restart\\|reconnect`, `config set`, `plugins install\\|setup`, `api setup`, and **`init-agent`** (writes `AGENTS.md` / `.cursor/rules` into the working repo — never default-run).\n- **Doc-level authoring:** all `create*` / `render*` / primitive aliases, `tokens *` writes, `var create\\|create-batch\\|bind-batch\\|set-batch\\|rename-batch\\|visualize`, `bind *`, `set *`, layout verbs (`sizing\\|padding\\|gap\\|align\\|set autolayout\\|set pin\\|arrange\\|unstack`), `duplicate`, `use\\|theme`, `node to-component`, `slot` writes, `sizes\\|variants\\|combos`, `shadcn add`, `blocks create`, `component prop add\\|combine`, `dev link\\|edit`, `section create\\|add`, `grid set`, `annotate add`, `import`, `lint --fix`, `screenshot-url`, `recreate-url`, `remove-bg`, `gradient extract --apply-to`, `gradient mesh`, and `fj` write verbs.\n\n### OMIT from the default path (destructive + arbitrary — explicit request only)\n\nKeep these out of the normal flow. Reach for them only on an explicit, specific user request, with the Section 6 / Section 7 ceremony:\n\n- **Destructive:** `var delete-all`, `var delete-batch`, `delete\\|remove`, `node delete`, `undo`, `unwrap`, `fj delete`, `plugins uninstall`, `dev unlink`, `component prop delete`, `grid clear`, `annotate clear`.\n- **Arbitrary mutation:** `eval`, `run`, `raw`, `fj eval`.\n\nWhere two readings of a command disagreed (e.g. `arrange` reads as \"destructive\" in one source comment but only repositions), the **stricter gating wins** in the SURFACE/GATE choice and the **accurate class wins** in the table — `arrange` is MUTATING (repositions), not DESTRUCTIVE (no delete).\n\n---\n\n## 5. THE LOCAL-EXPORT NO-OVERWRITE RULE\n\nRead-only does not mean side-effect-free on the local filesystem. `extract`, `export *`, `export-jsx`, `export-storybook`, `verify --save`, `analyze-url --screenshot`, and `api setup\\|index` all **write files locally**.\n\n1. **Always pass an explicit output path** (`-o file` / `[output]` / `--save path`). Do not rely on a default filename.\n2. **Never silently overwrite.** Check for an existing file first; if the target exists, choose a new path or ask before clobbering it.\n3. **Handle multi-file output.** `extract` auto-splits a large structure into a `DESIGN-structure/` directory above ~50k tokens — treat the export as a possible directory, not a single file.\n\nThese are local-filesystem mutations even though the Figma document is untouched. They never need Figma-side rollback, but they must not destroy prior local work.\n\n---\n\n## 6. THE DESTRUCTIVE SET (CONFIRM + EXPLICIT TARGET + ROLLBACK)\n\nNever run any of these without an explicit target (id / name / collection) and a stated rollback. **Never via an active-selection fallback.** The strongest rollback is to **duplicate the file / page / selection first** (`figma-ds-cli duplicate`, or a Figma page/file duplicate) — Figma's own **Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z)** and **version history** are the primary safety nets; the per-command notes below name the most direct recovery.\n\n| Destructive command | What it deletes | One-line rollback |\n| ------------------- | --------------- | ----------------- |\n| `var delete-all [-c collection]` | All local variables/collections (or one collection's) | Figma Undo immediately; otherwise restore from version history — irreversible once the session closes, so **duplicate the file first**. |\n| `var delete-batch <nodeIds>` | The listed nodes | Figma Undo; else version history. Confirm the exact id list before running. |\n| `delete\\|remove [nodeId]` | A node / current selection | Figma Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z); duplicate the node first for a safe copy. |\n| `node delete <nodeIds...>` | Nodes by id | Figma Undo; duplicate the nodes first. Require the explicit id list, not the selection. |\n| `undo` | The node(s) from the latest render / render-batch | Re-run the original `render` / `render-batch` to recreate; there is no \"redo\" for this CLI verb. |\n| `unwrap <nodeId> [--keep-wrapper]` | The wrapper frame (children survive) | Pass `--keep-wrapper` to avoid the delete; else Figma Undo restores the wrapper. |\n| `fj delete <nodeId> [-p]` | A FigJam node | Figma Undo on the FigJam page; duplicate the page first for large clears. |\n| `plugins uninstall <name>` | An installed plugin resource | Re-install with `plugins install <name>` (re-runs setup; any local plugin config is lost). |\n| `dev unlink` | A dev resource link | Re-create with `dev link` using the original URL — record the URL before unlinking. |\n| `component prop delete` | A component property | Re-create with `component prop add`; Figma Undo if still in-session. Note the prop name/type first. |\n| `grid clear` | Layout grid metadata on a node | Figma Undo; else re-apply with `grid set` from the recorded grid spec. |\n| `annotate clear` | Annotations | Figma Undo; else re-add with `annotate add` — copy the annotation text first. |\n\nRollback preference order, always: **(1) duplicate-first**, then **(2) Figma Undo (Cmd/Ctrl+Z) while still in-session**, then **(3) Figma version history**. State which one applies before you run the command.\n\n---\n\n## 7. THE ARBITRARY-MUTATION RULE (eval / raw / run / fj eval)\n\n`eval`, `run`, `raw`, and `fj eval` execute arbitrary Figma Plugin API code or arbitrary `figma-use` commands. They are not classified by name because the **payload** decides what they do — read, mutate, or delete.\n\n1. **Treat them as MUTATING at minimum, and as potentially DESTRUCTIVE.** Apply the GATE ceremony (confirm + target + rollback) by default, and the DESTRUCTIVE ceremony if the payload can delete.\n2. **Review the exact code / command before running it.** Never run `eval`/`run`/`raw` on an exploratory hunch or because the prompt \"sounds read-only.\"\n3. **Prefer the purpose-built verb.** The upstream agent rules state: never use `eval` to create visual nodes (it bypasses positioning and guards) — use `render` / `render-batch`. Reach for arbitrary execution only when no dedicated command exists.\n4. **Never delete existing user nodes** through arbitrary execution; the upstream generated rules prohibit it.\n\n---\n\n## 8. THE HARD RULE: VERIFY LIVE, GATE MUTATIONS\n\nThe command surface drifts between `REFERENCE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and the actual `src/commands/*.js`. The investigation found documented-but-unregistered commands (`voice`, `chat`, `prop combine`) and primitive-name drift (`REFERENCE.md` shows `create rect/circle/...`; source proves `create frame/icon/image` plus top-level `rect|ellipse|text|line|component|group|autolayout`). All of it must be hedged.\n\n1. **Verify with `<bin> <command> --help` before relying on a command.** A command in `REFERENCE.md`/`CLAUDE.md` may not exist in the installed binary, and flags differ between the npm `latest` (`1.0.0`) and repo `main` (`1.2.0`) builds. Examples in this skill are **illustrative; verify with `--help`.**\n2. **Verify the binary identity first.** Prefer `figma-ds-cli`; only trust `figma-cli` after `--version`/`--help` confirms it is the silships tool (the npm `figma-cli` package is unrelated). **Never `npm i -g figma-cli`.**\n3. **Gate every MUTATING verb** behind confirmation, an explicit target, and a one-line rollback.\n4. **Apply the DESTRUCTIVE ceremony** (Section 6) to every command in the destructive set: confirm + explicit target + rollback, prefer duplicate-first, never via the active-selection fallback.\n5. **Review every ARBITRARY payload** (Section 7) before it runs.\n6. **Enforce the export no-overwrite rule** (Section 5) on every local-file write, including \"read-only\" exports.\n7. **Never auto-apply the yolo `app.asar` patch** (`connect` without `--safe`) without explicit consent and a stated `figma-ds-cli unpatch` rollback. Prefer `connect --safe`.\n8. **Never expose the daemon token** (`~/.figma-ds-cli/.daemon-token`) in user-facing output; keep the daemon bound to `127.0.0.1`.\n\n---\n\n## 9. ESCALATION\n\n- **A command is not in this table, or `--help` disagrees with it.** Stop and verify with `<bin> <command> --help`; do not guess a class. The source drifts (Section 8).\n- **A destructive verb, a broad delete/undo/unwrap, or an arbitrary `eval`/`raw`/`run` is requested.** Describe the effect and the rollback, name the explicit target, then stop and wait for confirmation.\n- **The yolo patch is requested.** Surface the `app.asar` modification, the Figma-update fragility, and the `figma-ds-cli unpatch` rollback; prefer `connect --safe`; wait for consent.\n- **An export would overwrite an existing file.** Stop, name the conflicting path, and ask for a new path or explicit overwrite approval.\n- **Figma Desktop is not open or the daemon is unhealthy.** None of these commands work without the live Desktop session and a healthy daemon — escalate to setup before mutating.\n\n---\n\n## 10. REFERENCES\n\n- [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, command examples.\n- [mcp_wiring.md](mcp_wiring.md) - the optional Framelink Figma MCP via Code Mode (separate, opt-in surface).\n- [troubleshooting.md](troubleshooting.md) - failure modes and fixes.\n- [SKILL.md](../SKILL.md) - the skill contract this reference supports.\n- Packet research digest: `151-mcp-figma-with-direct-cli-support/001-figma-cli-and-mcp-research/research/iterations/iteration-001.md` (and `research/raw/iter-001.out` for the full per-flag table).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":273,"totalLines":273,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/tool_surface.md","time":{"start":1781459247447,"end":1781459247450}},"id":"prt_ec73ee154001c3hWbsQIfCkfBi","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459248028,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8d90427b46d24fa3a193c55f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/mcp_wiring.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/mcp_wiring.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\"\n3: description: \"Wiring the OPTIONAL Figma MCP into this project's Code Mode: the already-registered Framelink figma manual, the prefixed .env token, the discover-first flow, and a runnable call_tool_chain example. The CLI works fully alone; the MCP is opt-in.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"figma mcp\"\n6:   - \"figma mcp code mode\"\n7:   - \"figma-developer-mcp\"\n8:   - \"pull figma design context\"\n9:   - \"figma get_design_context\"\n10: importance_tier: \"normal\"\n11: contextType: \"implementation\"\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\n15: \n16: > **IMPORTANT:** This skill works **fully with the `figma-ds-cli` alone** — the MCP is **opt-in**. Before invoking any Figma MCP tool, always **discover first** (`search_tools` / `tool_info`) and confirm the `figma` manual and its exact tool names are present. Never guess a tool name, and never claim the MCP works until discovery confirms it.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Core Principle\n23: \n24: Wiring here means the agent reaches Figma's **read** surface — design context, variables, metadata — through this project's **Code Mode** transport. The Code Mode manual named `figma` is **already registered** in `.utcp_config.json` (community Framelink `figma-developer-mcp`, stdio, `npx`); nothing new needs to be installed for the MCP path. The only setup step is a `.env` entry with a Figma personal access token.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Pull Figma file/node data into the agent so it can generate or reconcile code against a design.\n29: - The work is codegen-from-design, not authoring or exporting from the live Desktop session.\n30: \n31: The CLI vs MCP routing line:\n32: \n33: - **`figma-ds-cli` (CLI) = author/modify/export IN Figma.** It drives the live Figma Desktop session to create/render/modify nodes, manage tokens and variables, and export assets/JSX/CSS/screenshots. This is the primary surface.\n34: - **Figma MCP (Code Mode) = pull design data INTO the agent for codegen.** Use it only when the agent needs Figma design context as model input (file/node data, variables, screenshots) to generate or align code. The MCP does not drive Figma Desktop.\n35: \n36: ### Key Sources\n37: \n38: - [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the primary CLI surface (binary identity, connect modes, daemon model) for authoring and exporting in Figma.\n39: - [tool_surface.md](tool_surface.md) - the CLI command gating taxonomy; the MCP path here is a separate, opt-in read surface, not part of that gating.\n40: - Code Mode mechanics (naming, prefixed env, discovery): [mcp-code-mode SKILL.md](../../mcp-code-mode/SKILL.md).\n41: \n42: Claims are tagged **[CONFIRMED]** (read from this repo's `.utcp_config.json` this session, or from the cited research digests) or **[INFERRED]** (reasoned, needs a live `tool_info()` / `list_tools()` to fix the exact string). The Framelink tool **names and input schemas are [INFERRED]** until a live discovery call confirms them, because the community server's per-tool schema is not pinned in this repo.\n43: \n44: ---\n45: \n46: ## 2. THE REGISTERED `figma` MANUAL\n47: \n48: The `figma` manual is already present in `.utcp_config.json` under `manual_call_templates[]`. Read it before changing anything. **[CONFIRMED — read from `.utcp_config.json` this session]**\n49: \n50: ```json\n51: {\n52:   \"name\": \"figma\",\n53:   \"call_template_type\": \"mcp\",\n54:   \"config\": {\n55:     \"mcpServers\": {\n56:       \"figma\": {\n57:         \"transport\": \"stdio\",\n58:         \"command\": \"npx\",\n59:         \"args\": [\"-y\", \"figma-developer-mcp@latest\", \"--stdio\"],\n60:         \"env\": { \"FIGMA_API_KEY\": \"${FIGMA_API_KEY}\" }\n61:       }\n62:     }\n63:   }\n64: }\n65: ```\n66: \n67: What it provides: the Framelink `figma-developer-mcp` server (npm `figma-developer-mcp`, v0.12.0 confirmed published) wraps the Figma REST API and **simplifies Figma file data for coding agents** — i.e. design context an agent can turn into code. **[CONFIRMED — research digest, npm view]** It is a **third-party** server, not Figma's official MCP. **[CONFIRMED]**\n68: \n69: Transport is **stdio** over `npx`, which matches every other manual registered here (`chrome_devtools_1/2`, `clickup_official`, `github` are all stdio). No HTTP manual exists in this repo, so the stdio Framelink path is the proven one. **[CONFIRMED — `.utcp_config.json` inspection]**\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 3. THE `.env` TOKEN (prefixed)\n74: \n75: The manual's config references `${FIGMA_API_KEY}`, but **Code Mode prefixes every environment variable with the manual name**. So the `.env` entry must be the **prefixed** form, not the bare name. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §4 \"Critical: Prefixed Environment Variables\"]**\n76: \n77: ```bash\n78: # .env (project root)\n79: figma_FIGMA_API_KEY=figd_your_token_here\n80: ```\n81: \n82: - The token is a **Figma personal access token** (begins `figd_`). Generate it in Figma → Settings → Security → personal access tokens. **[INFERRED — standard Figma token shape; verify in Figma]**\n83: - Using bare `FIGMA_API_KEY=...` will fail with `Error: Variable 'figma_FIGMA_API_KEY' not found`. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §4]**\n84: - This is the **only** setup the MCP path needs — the manual is already registered (Section 2). Never paste the token into user-facing output; treat it as a credential.\n85: \n86: | Manual name | Config reference   | `.env` variable        |\n87: | ----------- | ------------------ | ---------------------- |\n88: | `figma`     | `${FIGMA_API_KEY}` | `figma_FIGMA_API_KEY`  |\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 4. DISCOVER FIRST\n93: \n94: Code Mode loads tools progressively. Always discover before calling, because the Framelink tool names and input schemas are not pinned in this repo and the `figma-developer-mcp@latest` surface can change. **[INFERRED — server is `@latest`; names unverified here]**\n95: \n96: ```typescript\n97: // 1) Is the figma manual present, and what tools does it expose?\n98: const all = await list_tools();\n99: // group returned names by the prefix before the first dot; look for the \"figma\" group\n100: \n101: // 2) Search by intent to find the right Figma tool\n102: const tools = await search_tools({\n103:   task_description: \"get figma file or node design data for code generation\",\n104:   limit: 10\n105: });\n106: \n107: // 3) Confirm the exact callable syntax + input schema before invoking\n108: const info = await tool_info({ tool_name: \"figma.figma_get_figma_data\" });\n109: ```\n110: \n111: **Confirmed live surface (2026-06-14 `list_tools()`):** the `figma` manual currently exposes exactly two tools — **`figma.figma_get_figma_data`** (fetch a file/node's design data) and **`figma.figma_download_figma_images`** (download referenced images/SVGs). **[CONFIRMED — live Code Mode `list_tools()`]** Always re-run discovery, since `figma-developer-mcp@latest` can change its surface; treat input schemas as `tool_info()`-verified, not assumed.\n112: \n113: `list_tools()` returns names in dotted (`a.b.c`) form; the **callable** form uses an underscore between the manual prefix and the tool: `figma.figma_<tool>`. `tool_info()` shows the correct calling syntax and the expected params. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §3 naming + tool-name translation]**\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## 5. CALL EXAMPLE (`call_tool_chain`)\n118: \n119: > Illustrative — the exact tool name and params are placeholders. Run `tool_info()` (Section 4) to fix `<tool>` and its arguments before relying on this.\n120: \n121: Naming pattern is `{manual}.{manual}_{tool}`, so every Framelink call is `figma.figma_<tool>`. Wrap calls in try/catch and return structured state. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §3]**\n122: \n123: ```typescript\n124: await call_tool_chain({\n125:   code: `\n126:     try {\n127:       // Tool name confirmed via list_tools(); confirm the param schema with tool_info() first.\n128:       const file = await figma.figma_get_figma_data({\n129:         // fileKey / nodeId pulled from a Figma design URL:\n130:         // https://www.figma.com/design/FILE_KEY/Name?node-id=NODE_ID\n131:         fileKey: \"FILE_KEY\",\n132:         nodeId: \"NODE_ID\",\n133:         context: \"Pull Figma node data to generate a matching component\"\n134:       });\n135:       return { success: true, source: \"figma_framelink\", file };\n136:     } catch (err) {\n137:       return { success: false, error: String(err) };\n138:     }\n139:   `\n140: });\n141: ```\n142: \n143: Notes:\n144: \n145: - The Framelink server reads Figma via the REST API using the `.env` token — Figma Desktop does **not** need to be open for the MCP path (that requirement is the CLI's, not the MCP's). **[INFERRED — Framelink is API-backed, not Desktop-backed]**\n146: - Static manuals registered in `.utcp_config.json` need no cleanup; only dynamically registered manuals (`register_manual`) require `deregister_manual`. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2]**\n147: - MCP responses can be token-heavy. Prefer narrow, node-scoped calls over whole-file pulls when the schema allows it. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2 gotchas]**\n148: \n149: ---\n150: \n151: ## 6. OFFICIAL FIGMA DEV MODE MCP (out of scope this release)\n152: \n153: Figma also ships an **official** Dev Mode MCP server (a remote `https://mcp.figma.com/mcp` server and a desktop-local `http://127.0.0.1:3845/mcp` server, both HTTP MCP with OAuth/desktop-session auth). **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2]** It is **not a supported path in this release** and is **not documented here**:\n154: \n155: - Code Mode has **no HTTP manual registered** in this repo — every manual is stdio — so the official HTTP transport is unproven here. **[CONFIRMED — `.utcp_config.json` inspection]**\n156: - The remote server is **catalog/OAuth-gated**; whether this project's Code Mode client is admitted is **unverified**. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2 unknowns]**\n157: \n158: Treat the official Dev Mode MCP as a **future option only**. Do not wire or recommend it as a supported route in this version; the registered Framelink `figma` manual (Sections 2–5) is the supported MCP path for now.\n159: \n160: ---\n161: \n162: ## 7. REFERENCES\n163: \n164: - [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the primary CLI surface: binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, and command examples.\n165: - [tool_surface.md](tool_surface.md) - the CLI read-only / mutating / destructive taxonomy and gating.\n166: - [troubleshooting.md](troubleshooting.md) - failures including the Code Mode env-var prefix (`figma_FIGMA_API_KEY`) and tools-not-discovered cases.\n167: - [utcp_figma_manual.md](../assets/utcp_figma_manual.md) - the runnable Code Mode manual companion (the `figma` manual entry and ready-to-run `call_tool_chain` snippets).\n168: - [SKILL.md](../SKILL.md) - the skill contract these references support; see §3 \"Optional Figma MCP via Code Mode\".\n169: - Code Mode mechanics (naming, prefixed env, discovery): [mcp-code-mode SKILL.md](../../mcp-code-mode/SKILL.md).\n\n(End of file - total 169 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\"\ndescription: \"Wiring the OPTIONAL Figma MCP into this project's Code Mode: the already-registered Framelink figma manual, the prefixed .env token, the discover-first flow, and a runnable call_tool_chain example. The CLI works fully alone; the MCP is opt-in.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"figma mcp\"\n  - \"figma mcp code mode\"\n  - \"figma-developer-mcp\"\n  - \"pull figma design context\"\n  - \"figma get_design_context\"\nimportance_tier: \"normal\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n---\n\n# Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\n\n> **IMPORTANT:** This skill works **fully with the `figma-ds-cli` alone** — the MCP is **opt-in**. Before invoking any Figma MCP tool, always **discover first** (`search_tools` / `tool_info`) and confirm the `figma` manual and its exact tool names are present. Never guess a tool name, and never claim the MCP works until discovery confirms it.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/mcp_wiring.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\"\ndescription: \"Wiring the OPTIONAL Figma MCP into this project's Code Mode: the already-registered Framelink figma manual, the prefixed .env token, the discover-first flow, and a runnable call_tool_chain example. The CLI works fully alone; the MCP is opt-in.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"figma mcp\"\n  - \"figma mcp code mode\"\n  - \"figma-developer-mcp\"\n  - \"pull figma design context\"\n  - \"figma get_design_context\"\nimportance_tier: \"normal\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n---\n\n# Figma MCP Wiring (optional, via Code Mode)\n\n> **IMPORTANT:** This skill works **fully with the `figma-ds-cli` alone** — the MCP is **opt-in**. Before invoking any Figma MCP tool, always **discover first** (`search_tools` / `tool_info`) and confirm the `figma` manual and its exact tool names are present. Never guess a tool name, and never claim the MCP works until discovery confirms it.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\nWiring here means the agent reaches Figma's **read** surface — design context, variables, metadata — through this project's **Code Mode** transport. The Code Mode manual named `figma` is **already registered** in `.utcp_config.json` (community Framelink `figma-developer-mcp`, stdio, `npx`); nothing new needs to be installed for the MCP path. The only setup step is a `.env` entry with a Figma personal access token.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Pull Figma file/node data into the agent so it can generate or reconcile code against a design.\n- The work is codegen-from-design, not authoring or exporting from the live Desktop session.\n\nThe CLI vs MCP routing line:\n\n- **`figma-ds-cli` (CLI) = author/modify/export IN Figma.** It drives the live Figma Desktop session to create/render/modify nodes, manage tokens and variables, and export assets/JSX/CSS/screenshots. This is the primary surface.\n- **Figma MCP (Code Mode) = pull design data INTO the agent for codegen.** Use it only when the agent needs Figma design context as model input (file/node data, variables, screenshots) to generate or align code. The MCP does not drive Figma Desktop.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n- [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the primary CLI surface (binary identity, connect modes, daemon model) for authoring and exporting in Figma.\n- [tool_surface.md](tool_surface.md) - the CLI command gating taxonomy; the MCP path here is a separate, opt-in read surface, not part of that gating.\n- Code Mode mechanics (naming, prefixed env, discovery): [mcp-code-mode SKILL.md](../../mcp-code-mode/SKILL.md).\n\nClaims are tagged **[CONFIRMED]** (read from this repo's `.utcp_config.json` this session, or from the cited research digests) or **[INFERRED]** (reasoned, needs a live `tool_info()` / `list_tools()` to fix the exact string). The Framelink tool **names and input schemas are [INFERRED]** until a live discovery call confirms them, because the community server's per-tool schema is not pinned in this repo.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE REGISTERED `figma` MANUAL\n\nThe `figma` manual is already present in `.utcp_config.json` under `manual_call_templates[]`. Read it before changing anything. **[CONFIRMED — read from `.utcp_config.json` this session]**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"figma\",\n  \"call_template_type\": \"mcp\",\n  \"config\": {\n    \"mcpServers\": {\n      \"figma\": {\n        \"transport\": \"stdio\",\n        \"command\": \"npx\",\n        \"args\": [\"-y\", \"figma-developer-mcp@latest\", \"--stdio\"],\n        \"env\": { \"FIGMA_API_KEY\": \"${FIGMA_API_KEY}\" }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWhat it provides: the Framelink `figma-developer-mcp` server (npm `figma-developer-mcp`, v0.12.0 confirmed published) wraps the Figma REST API and **simplifies Figma file data for coding agents** — i.e. design context an agent can turn into code. **[CONFIRMED — research digest, npm view]** It is a **third-party** server, not Figma's official MCP. **[CONFIRMED]**\n\nTransport is **stdio** over `npx`, which matches every other manual registered here (`chrome_devtools_1/2`, `clickup_official`, `github` are all stdio). No HTTP manual exists in this repo, so the stdio Framelink path is the proven one. **[CONFIRMED — `.utcp_config.json` inspection]**\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE `.env` TOKEN (prefixed)\n\nThe manual's config references `${FIGMA_API_KEY}`, but **Code Mode prefixes every environment variable with the manual name**. So the `.env` entry must be the **prefixed** form, not the bare name. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §4 \"Critical: Prefixed Environment Variables\"]**\n\n```bash\n# .env (project root)\nfigma_FIGMA_API_KEY=figd_your_token_here\n```\n\n- The token is a **Figma personal access token** (begins `figd_`). Generate it in Figma → Settings → Security → personal access tokens. **[INFERRED — standard Figma token shape; verify in Figma]**\n- Using bare `FIGMA_API_KEY=...` will fail with `Error: Variable 'figma_FIGMA_API_KEY' not found`. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §4]**\n- This is the **only** setup the MCP path needs — the manual is already registered (Section 2). Never paste the token into user-facing output; treat it as a credential.\n\n| Manual name | Config reference   | `.env` variable        |\n| ----------- | ------------------ | ---------------------- |\n| `figma`     | `${FIGMA_API_KEY}` | `figma_FIGMA_API_KEY`  |\n\n---\n\n## 4. DISCOVER FIRST\n\nCode Mode loads tools progressively. Always discover before calling, because the Framelink tool names and input schemas are not pinned in this repo and the `figma-developer-mcp@latest` surface can change. **[INFERRED — server is `@latest`; names unverified here]**\n\n```typescript\n// 1) Is the figma manual present, and what tools does it expose?\nconst all = await list_tools();\n// group returned names by the prefix before the first dot; look for the \"figma\" group\n\n// 2) Search by intent to find the right Figma tool\nconst tools = await search_tools({\n  task_description: \"get figma file or node design data for code generation\",\n  limit: 10\n});\n\n// 3) Confirm the exact callable syntax + input schema before invoking\nconst info = await tool_info({ tool_name: \"figma.figma_get_figma_data\" });\n```\n\n**Confirmed live surface (2026-06-14 `list_tools()`):** the `figma` manual currently exposes exactly two tools — **`figma.figma_get_figma_data`** (fetch a file/node's design data) and **`figma.figma_download_figma_images`** (download referenced images/SVGs). **[CONFIRMED — live Code Mode `list_tools()`]** Always re-run discovery, since `figma-developer-mcp@latest` can change its surface; treat input schemas as `tool_info()`-verified, not assumed.\n\n`list_tools()` returns names in dotted (`a.b.c`) form; the **callable** form uses an underscore between the manual prefix and the tool: `figma.figma_<tool>`. `tool_info()` shows the correct calling syntax and the expected params. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §3 naming + tool-name translation]**\n\n---\n\n## 5. CALL EXAMPLE (`call_tool_chain`)\n\n> Illustrative — the exact tool name and params are placeholders. Run `tool_info()` (Section 4) to fix `<tool>` and its arguments before relying on this.\n\nNaming pattern is `{manual}.{manual}_{tool}`, so every Framelink call is `figma.figma_<tool>`. Wrap calls in try/catch and return structured state. **[CONFIRMED — mcp-code-mode SKILL.md §3]**\n\n```typescript\nawait call_tool_chain({\n  code: `\n    try {\n      // Tool name confirmed via list_tools(); confirm the param schema with tool_info() first.\n      const file = await figma.figma_get_figma_data({\n        // fileKey / nodeId pulled from a Figma design URL:\n        // https://www.figma.com/design/FILE_KEY/Name?node-id=NODE_ID\n        fileKey: \"FILE_KEY\",\n        nodeId: \"NODE_ID\",\n        context: \"Pull Figma node data to generate a matching component\"\n      });\n      return { success: true, source: \"figma_framelink\", file };\n    } catch (err) {\n      return { success: false, error: String(err) };\n    }\n  `\n});\n```\n\nNotes:\n\n- The Framelink server reads Figma via the REST API using the `.env` token — Figma Desktop does **not** need to be open for the MCP path (that requirement is the CLI's, not the MCP's). **[INFERRED — Framelink is API-backed, not Desktop-backed]**\n- Static manuals registered in `.utcp_config.json` need no cleanup; only dynamically registered manuals (`register_manual`) require `deregister_manual`. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2]**\n- MCP responses can be token-heavy. Prefer narrow, node-scoped calls over whole-file pulls when the schema allows it. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2 gotchas]**\n\n---\n\n## 6. OFFICIAL FIGMA DEV MODE MCP (out of scope this release)\n\nFigma also ships an **official** Dev Mode MCP server (a remote `https://mcp.figma.com/mcp` server and a desktop-local `http://127.0.0.1:3845/mcp` server, both HTTP MCP with OAuth/desktop-session auth). **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2]** It is **not a supported path in this release** and is **not documented here**:\n\n- Code Mode has **no HTTP manual registered** in this repo — every manual is stdio — so the official HTTP transport is unproven here. **[CONFIRMED — `.utcp_config.json` inspection]**\n- The remote server is **catalog/OAuth-gated**; whether this project's Code Mode client is admitted is **unverified**. **[CONFIRMED — research digest IT2 unknowns]**\n\nTreat the official Dev Mode MCP as a **future option only**. Do not wire or recommend it as a supported route in this version; the registered Framelink `figma` manual (Sections 2–5) is the supported MCP path for now.\n\n---\n\n## 7. REFERENCES\n\n- [figma_cli_reference.md](figma_cli_reference.md) - the primary CLI surface: binary identity, connect modes, daemon model, and command examples.\n- [tool_surface.md](tool_surface.md) - the CLI read-only / mutating / destructive taxonomy and gating.\n- [troubleshooting.md](troubleshooting.md) - failures including the Code Mode env-var prefix (`figma_FIGMA_API_KEY`) and tools-not-discovered cases.\n- [utcp_figma_manual.md](../assets/utcp_figma_manual.md) - the runnable Code Mode manual companion (the `figma` manual entry and ready-to-run `call_tool_chain` snippets).\n- [SKILL.md](../SKILL.md) - the skill contract these references support; see §3 \"Optional Figma MCP via Code Mode\".\n- Code Mode mechanics (naming, prefixed env, discovery): [mcp-code-mode SKILL.md](../../mcp-code-mode/SKILL.md).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":169,"totalLines":169,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/references/mcp_wiring.md","time":{"start":1781459248025,"end":1781459248027}},"id":"prt_ec73ee397001r5X41VSvjWgZrm","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459248628,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_c7c6f79379f14448829f3aef","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-safe.sh"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-safe.sh</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n2: # Guided SAFE connect (FigCli plugin bridge). Never patches Figma Desktop.\n3: \n4: set -euo pipefail\n5: HERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n6: # shellcheck source=_common.sh\n7: . \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n8: \n9: b=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first (do NOT 'npm i -g figma-cli')\"; exit 1; }\n10: figma_desktop_path >/dev/null || warn \"Figma Desktop not found; safe connect needs it open with a file.\"\n11: \n12: cat <<EOF\n13: == SAFE connect (no patch) ==\n14: Safe mode uses the FigCli plugin instead of patching Figma Desktop.\n15: Before continuing, in Figma Desktop:\n16:   1) Open the target Figma file.\n17:   2) One-time: import the FigCli plugin manifest (plugin/manifest.json from the figma-cli install).\n18:   3) Open: Plugins -> Development -> FigCli  (keep it open during the session).\n19: EOF\n20: printf 'Proceed with safe connect now? [y/N] '\n21: read -r ans\n22: case \"$ans\" in y|Y|yes|YES) ;; *) info \"Aborted.\"; exit 0;; esac\n23: \n24: info \"Running: $b connect --safe\"\n25: \"$b\" connect --safe\n26: info \"Daemon status:\"; \"$b\" daemon status || warn \"daemon status failed; try: $HERE/daemon.sh diagnose\"\n\n(End of file - total 26 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Guided SAFE connect (FigCli plugin bridge). Never patches Figma Desktop.\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first (do NOT 'npm i -g figma-cli')\"; exit 1; }\nfigma_desktop_path >/dev/null || warn \"Figma Desktop not found; safe connect needs it open with a file.\"\n\ncat <<EOF\n== SAFE connect (no patch) ==\nSafe mode uses the FigCli plugin instead of patching Figma Desktop.\nBefore continuing, in Figma Desktop:\n  1) Open the target Figma file.\n  2) One-time: import the FigCli plugin manifest (plugin/manifest.json from the figma-cli install).\n  3) Open: Plugins -> Development -> FigCli  (keep it open during the session).\nEOF\nprintf 'Proceed with safe connect now? [y/N] '","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-safe.sh","text":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Guided SAFE connect (FigCli plugin bridge). Never patches Figma Desktop.\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first (do NOT 'npm i -g figma-cli')\"; exit 1; }\nfigma_desktop_path >/dev/null || warn \"Figma Desktop not found; safe connect needs it open with a file.\"\n\ncat <<EOF\n== SAFE connect (no patch) ==\nSafe mode uses the FigCli plugin instead of patching Figma Desktop.\nBefore continuing, in Figma Desktop:\n  1) Open the target Figma file.\n  2) One-time: import the FigCli plugin manifest (plugin/manifest.json from the figma-cli install).\n  3) Open: Plugins -> Development -> FigCli  (keep it open during the session).\nEOF\nprintf 'Proceed with safe connect now? [y/N] '\nread -r ans\ncase \"$ans\" in y|Y|yes|YES) ;; *) info \"Aborted.\"; exit 0;; esac\n\ninfo \"Running: $b connect --safe\"\n\"$b\" connect --safe\ninfo \"Daemon status:\"; \"$b\" daemon status || warn \"daemon status failed; try: $HERE/daemon.sh diagnose\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":26,"totalLines":26,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-safe.sh","time":{"start":1781459248626,"end":1781459248628}},"id":"prt_ec73ee5f00014VtdW4t5liQxAQ","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459248910,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_543646a159824cc98d461bf5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-yolo.sh"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-yolo.sh</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n2: # YOLO connect — PATCHES Figma Desktop (app.asar) and restarts it with CDP on 9222.\n3: # Gated behind an explicit consent flag. Rollback: unpatch.sh (figma-ds-cli unpatch).\n4: \n5: set -euo pipefail\n6: HERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n7: # shellcheck source=_common.sh\n8: . \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n9: \n10: CONSENT=0\n11: [ \"${1:-}\" = \"--i-understand-this-patches-figma\" ] && CONSENT=1\n12: \n13: if [ \"$CONSENT\" != 1 ]; then\n14:   cat >&2 <<EOF\n15: ${_c_ylw}REFUSED: yolo connect patches Figma Desktop.${_c_rst}\n16: \n17: Effect:  modifies Figma's app.asar (remote-debugging switch), codesigns the app\n18:          on macOS, restarts Figma, and exposes CDP on 127.0.0.1:$CDP_PORT.\n19: Risks:   may require Full Disk Access / admin; a Figma update can invalidate the\n20:          patch and require re-running connect.\n21: Rollback: $HERE/unpatch.sh   (runs: figma-ds-cli unpatch)\n22: \n23: Prefer SAFE mode: $HERE/connect-safe.sh\n24: To proceed anyway, re-run with: $0 --i-understand-this-patches-figma\n25: EOF\n26:   exit 2\n27: fi\n28: \n29: b=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first\"; exit 1; }\n30: figma_desktop_path >/dev/null || { err \"Figma Desktop not found; cannot patch.\"; exit 1; }\n31: \n32: warn \"Consent received. Patching Figma Desktop and starting yolo connect.\"\n33: info \"Running: $b connect\"\n34: \"$b\" connect\n35: info \"Daemon status:\"; \"$b\" daemon status || warn \"daemon status failed; try: $HERE/daemon.sh diagnose\"\n36: info \"Rollback any time with: $HERE/unpatch.sh\"\n\n(End of file - total 36 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# YOLO connect — PATCHES Figma Desktop (app.asar) and restarts it with CDP on 9222.\n# Gated behind an explicit consent flag. Rollback: unpatch.sh (figma-ds-cli unpatch).\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nCONSENT=0\n[ \"${1:-}\" = \"--i-understand-this-patches-figma\" ] && CONSENT=1\n\nif [ \"$CONSENT\" != 1 ]; then\n  cat >&2 <<EOF\n${_c_ylw}REFUSED: yolo connect patches Figma Desktop.${_c_rst}\n\nEffect:  modifies Figma's app.asar (remote-debugging switch), codesigns the app\n         on macOS, restarts Figma, and exposes CDP on 127.0.0.1:$CDP_PORT.\nRisks:   may require Full Disk Access / admin; a Figma update can invalidate the\n         patch and require re-running connect.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-yolo.sh","text":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# YOLO connect — PATCHES Figma Desktop (app.asar) and restarts it with CDP on 9222.\n# Gated behind an explicit consent flag. Rollback: unpatch.sh (figma-ds-cli unpatch).\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nCONSENT=0\n[ \"${1:-}\" = \"--i-understand-this-patches-figma\" ] && CONSENT=1\n\nif [ \"$CONSENT\" != 1 ]; then\n  cat >&2 <<EOF\n${_c_ylw}REFUSED: yolo connect patches Figma Desktop.${_c_rst}\n\nEffect:  modifies Figma's app.asar (remote-debugging switch), codesigns the app\n         on macOS, restarts Figma, and exposes CDP on 127.0.0.1:$CDP_PORT.\nRisks:   may require Full Disk Access / admin; a Figma update can invalidate the\n         patch and require re-running connect.\nRollback: $HERE/unpatch.sh   (runs: figma-ds-cli unpatch)\n\nPrefer SAFE mode: $HERE/connect-safe.sh\nTo proceed anyway, re-run with: $0 --i-understand-this-patches-figma\nEOF\n  exit 2\nfi\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first\"; exit 1; }\nfigma_desktop_path >/dev/null || { err \"Figma Desktop not found; cannot patch.\"; exit 1; }\n\nwarn \"Consent received. Patching Figma Desktop and starting yolo connect.\"\ninfo \"Running: $b connect\"\n\"$b\" connect\ninfo \"Daemon status:\"; \"$b\" daemon status || warn \"daemon status failed; try: $HERE/daemon.sh diagnose\"\ninfo \"Rollback any time with: $HERE/unpatch.sh\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":36,"totalLines":36,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/connect-yolo.sh","time":{"start":1781459248907,"end":1781459248909}},"id":"prt_ec73ee708001TtAkpY2hFOqNTn","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459249425,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cced6b5f9bc3494c9872b1c0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/daemon.sh"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/daemon.sh</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n2: # Thin wrapper over `figma-ds-cli daemon <verb>`. Read verbs are safe; start/stop/\n3: # restart/reconnect change daemon state (not the Figma document).\n4: \n5: set -euo pipefail\n6: HERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n7: # shellcheck source=_common.sh\n8: . \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n9: \n10: verb=\"${1:-status}\"\n11: case \"$verb\" in\n12:   status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect) ;;\n13:   -h|--help|help) echo \"Usage: daemon.sh {status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect}\"; exit 0;;\n14:   *) err \"Unknown daemon verb: $verb\"; echo \"Use: status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect\" >&2; exit 2;;\n15: esac\n16: \n17: b=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first\"; exit 1; }\n18: info \"Running: $b daemon $verb\"\n19: \"$b\" daemon \"$verb\"\n\n(End of file - total 19 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Thin wrapper over `figma-ds-cli daemon <verb>`. Read verbs are safe; start/stop/\n# restart/reconnect change daemon state (not the Figma document).\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nverb=\"${1:-status}\"\ncase \"$verb\" in\n  status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect) ;;\n  -h|--help|help) echo \"Usage: daemon.sh {status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect}\"; exit 0;;\n  *) err \"Unknown daemon verb: $verb\"; echo \"Use: status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect\" >&2; exit 2;;\nesac\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first\"; exit 1; }\ninfo \"Running: $b daemon $verb\"\n\"$b\" daemon \"$verb\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/daemon.sh","text":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Thin wrapper over `figma-ds-cli daemon <verb>`. Read verbs are safe; start/stop/\n# restart/reconnect change daemon state (not the Figma document).\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nverb=\"${1:-status}\"\ncase \"$verb\" in\n  status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect) ;;\n  -h|--help|help) echo \"Usage: daemon.sh {status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect}\"; exit 0;;\n  *) err \"Unknown daemon verb: $verb\"; echo \"Use: status|diagnose|start|stop|restart|reconnect\" >&2; exit 2;;\nesac\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH — run install.sh first\"; exit 1; }\ninfo \"Running: $b daemon $verb\"\n\"$b\" daemon \"$verb\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":19,"totalLines":19,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/daemon.sh","time":{"start":1781459249421,"end":1781459249424}},"id":"prt_ec73ee90a0011ekcyRKrpsjNSf","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781459249894,"sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_e96da9d9245c4d7ebd5e8a1d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/unpatch.sh"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/unpatch.sh</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n2: # Roll back the yolo patch: restore Figma Desktop's original app.asar.\n3: \n4: set -euo pipefail\n5: HERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n6: # shellcheck source=_common.sh\n7: . \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n8: \n9: b=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH\"; exit 1; }\n10: info \"Running: $b unpatch  (restores Figma Desktop to its original state)\"\n11: \"$b\" unpatch\n12: ok \"Unpatch complete. If Figma still misbehaves, update/reinstall Figma Desktop, then reconnect with connect-safe.sh.\"\n\n(End of file - total 12 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Roll back the yolo patch: restore Figma Desktop's original app.asar.\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH\"; exit 1; }\ninfo \"Running: $b unpatch  (restores Figma Desktop to its original state)\"\n\"$b\" unpatch\nok \"Unpatch complete. If Figma still misbehaves, update/reinstall Figma Desktop, then reconnect with connect-safe.sh.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/unpatch.sh","text":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Roll back the yolo patch: restore Figma Desktop's original app.asar.\n\nset -euo pipefail\nHERE=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\n# shellcheck source=_common.sh\n. \"$HERE/_common.sh\"\n\nb=\"$(figma_bin)\" || { err \"No figma-ds-cli on PATH\"; exit 1; }\ninfo \"Running: $b unpatch  (restores Figma Desktop to its original state)\"\n\"$b\" unpatch\nok \"Unpatch complete. If Figma still misbehaves, update/reinstall Figma Desktop, then reconnect with connect-safe.sh.\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":12,"totalLines":12,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/mcp-figma/scripts/unpatch.sh","time":{"start":1781459249890,"end":1781459249894}},"id":"prt_ec73eeae0001SP1jiSIA3FMASN","sessionID":"ses_138c2bb01ffeUjkBZZt6lKZbis","messageID":"msg_ec73ed580001dHI00Dk3D13x1d"}}
